(429, 'France', 'Crime Risk', 'internationalsos', '2021-05-14', 'Not Recieved', '\nFor travellers:\n‚Ä¢ Defer all non-essential travel due to the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.\nFor those in country:\n‚Ä¢ Monitor this alert.\n‚Ä¢ Follow the advice and requirements of local authorities\n‚Ä¢ Closely monitor the extent of transmission in your location.\n‚Ä¢ Keep yourself in the best possible health. Get the recommended amount of sleep each\nday, eat a healthy diet, and keep up regular physical activity.\n‚Ä¢ Limit face-to-face contact with others, stay home as much as practically possible.\n‚Ä¢ Practice social distancing: Keep 2 metres (6 feet) away from other people. Consider\nwhether gatherings with friends and family should be minimised. Avoid large and small\ngatherings in public. Avoid crowds.\n‚Ä¢ Wear a mask whenever required to. Wear a mask when in public, especially if it is not\npossible to keep 2 metres (6 feet) away from others.\n‚Ä¢ Cough and sneeze into your elbow, not your hands.\n‚Ä¢ Do not shake hands, hug or kiss.\n‚Ä¢ Wash your hands frequently. Carry hand sanitiser for use when soap and water are not\nreadily available.\n‚Ä¢ Avoid sharing food, drinks and personal items.\n‚Ä¢ Avoid touching your face. If you must touch objects which are handled by many people\n(such as handrails, doorknobs) ensure you do not touch your face. Wash your hands /\nclean them with hand sanitiser soon as possible.\nFor those who have any symptoms:\n‚Ä¢ Stay at home and do not have contact with others. Call for medical advice. Follow the\nlocal procedure for your area for getting tested.\n‚Ä¢ It is likely that mild cases will remain at home, in isolation from others, for the duration\nof the illness.\n‚Ä¢ If seeking in-person medical care, wear a mask. Use private transport and avoid\ncontact with others as much as possible.\n‚Ä¢ Do not travel if you are sick.\n', '\nPapua New Guinea: COVID-19 outbreak\n', '0', '3', '', ' -Advisory: Papua New Guinea -COVID-19outbreak\n', NULL),
(430, 'Australia', 'Crime Risk', 'internationalsos', '2021-05-19', 'Not Recieved', '\nInbound travellers\n‚Ä¢ Essential travel to Papua New Guinea can resume with stringent precautions ,factoring\nintheeffectsoftheCOVID-19pandemic.Thisassessmentismadejointlybyour health\nand security professionals.\nManagers\n‚Ä¢ Continue to maintain your international staff in two groups for planning purposes:\no Essential staff who are prepared to remain in an environment of reduced health\ncapabilities and increased mobility restrictions. This group should implement\ntheir stand-fast plan and adopt flexible working arrangements, where possible.\no Non-essential staff and their dependants in Papua New Guinea, as well as\ndependants of essential staff, whom you will prioritise for outbound travel in\ncase the operational risk environment deteriorates.\n‚Ä¢ Closely monitor developments for any further announcements by the authorities,\nincluding the imposition of additional mobility restrictions by the National Control Centre\nfor COVID-19 and changes to restrictions on flights to international destinations.\n‚Ä¢ Revise your Business Continuity Plans (BCP) and ensure they are implemented.\n‚Ä¢ For the entire workforce, including local staff, ensure strict compliance with National\nControl Centre restrictions.\nIn-country workforce\n‚Ä¢ Abide by all official directives. People currently in Papua New Guinea should consider\norganisation- specific requirements. Ensure you have provisions in place at your\naccommodation and work sites for at least two weeks.\n‚Ä¢ If you decide to depart, reconfirm your flight itinerary with the relevant airline.We do not\nhold information on specific flights. Allow additional time for all journeys to account for\npotential screening measures at ports of arrival and departure.\n‚Ä¢ If you plan to remain in Papua New Guinea, review your visa status to avoid any\nfinancial and legal repercussions.\n‚Ä¢ Closely monitor developments, including any announcements pertaining to internal\ntravel restrictions and protests against such measures.\n‚Ä¢ For any additional queries or more itinerary- specific health and travel advice, call\nInternational SOS.\nHealth advice\n‚Ä¢ Obtain profile-specific advice prior to any travel, taking into account the extent to which\nyour age and health may make you more vulnerable to the COVID-19 virus.\n‚Ä¢ Do not travel if you are sick. People who are sick face the risk of being tested and\nquarantined. Monitor your health and seek medical attention if you develop flu-like\nsymptoms, following the local procedure for your location.\n‚Ä¢ Pay strict attention to hygiene. Wash your hands frequently and carry hand sanitiser for\nuse when soap and water are not readily available. Wear a mask whenever required\nto. Even if not required, consider wearing a mask if you have to go out in public.\n‚Ä¢ Avoid crowded places. In public areas, as much as possible, keep three-to-six feet (1-2\nmetres) away from others.\nASSISTANCE\n', '\nPapua New Guinea: Evacuation level reduced to STAND BY due\nto improved inbound, outbound mobility options\n', '0', '3', '', ' -Advisory: Papua New Guinea -Evacuation level reduced to STAND BY due to\nimproved inbound, outbound mobility options\n', NULL),
