(514, 'Israel', 'Crime Risk', 'internationalsos', '2021-05-14', 'Not Recieved', '\nInbound business travellers\n‚Ä¢ Defer all travel to Israel and the Palestinian Territories until at least 17 May due to the\ncurrent security escalation and entry restrictions related to the COVID-19 pandemic.\nIn-country workforce\n‚Ä¢ Minimise non-essential movement in Central, Southern and Tel Aviv districts (all\nIsrael). Abide by all official directives issued by the emergency services and civil\nauthorities. Stay in the vicinity of the nearest shelter or protected space.\n‚Ä¢ Defer all travel to locations within 25 miles (40km) of the border with Gaza.\n‚Ä¢ Understand the immediate actions to take upon hearing an air raid siren and remain\naware of the location of the nearest shelter or protected space. The length of an air raid\nsiren represents the amount of time one has to enter their secure space. When in a\nsecure space, remain there for at least ten minutes. If another air raid warning is heard\nduring this time, remain inside the secure space for a further ten minutes.\n‚Ä¢ For further information on what to do during a rocket attack, please visit the IDF Home\nFront Command website (access from outside Israel may not be possible) and consult\nFront Command website (access from outside Israel may not be possible) and consult\nthis Preparedness Information document.\n‚Ä¢ Maintain situational awareness and exercise vigilance due to the potential for militant\nattacks. Targets may include religious gatherings, public transport, security force\npremises and personnel and locations where members of the ultra-Orthodox Jewish\ncommunity or those of perceived Arab ethnicity regularly gather.\n‚Ä¢ Ensure regular check-ins with line managers and other in-country workforce. Keep\nemergency contact details (such as phone numbers) on your person.\n‚Ä¢ Avoid all gatherings due to the risk of unrest and a significant security force response.\nIn areas affected by recurrent unrest, minimise movement after dark due to the\npotential for further violence. Liaise with local contacts and monitor local news to\nremain apprised of developments. Expect, but do not be unduly alarmed by, a\nheightened security force presence. Always carry relevant identification and follow all\ndirectives of the security forces.\n‚Ä¢ As Israeli airspace and Ben Gurion International Airport (TLV, Tel Aviv) may be\nperiodically closed, reconfirm all flight itineraries in the coming days and anticipate\nresidual disruption at the airport after such closures.\n‚Ä¢ Abide by all COVID-19-related regulations. Do not attempt to bypass any restrictions\nunless cleared to do so.\n‚Ä¢ The above advice is not exhaustive. Consult our Standing Travel Advice for Israel and\nthe Palestinian Territories for full recommendations.\nJerusalem\n‚Ä¢ Defer visits to Jerusalem‚Äôs Old City and flashpoint neighbourhoods until at least 17\nMay. Exercise caution and be prepared to leave an area at the first sign of unrest\nshould you wish to visit the area, particularly the Temple Mount/Haram al-Sharif\ncomplex, which houses al-Aqsa mosque. Ensure you have emergency contact\nnumbers on your person.\nWest Bank (Palestinian Territories)\n‚Ä¢ Abide by the current COVID-19 restrictions related to the ongoing lockdown.\n‚Ä¢ Avoid all gatherings due to the risk of localised unrest. Exercise caution if travelling in\nthe vicinity of Israeli settlements, as well as on routes and junctions leading to them\nand their surrounding areas.\n‚Ä¢ Have flexible travel plans as the Israeli security forces may impose curfews, travel\nbans, road closures or similar restrictions in areas of the West Bank with little or no\nnotice.\nGaza\n‚Ä¢ We continue to advise against all travel to Gaza, where the travel risks are rated as\nEXTREME. Organisations with workforce in Gaza should contact us for itinerary- and\nprofile-specific security advice.\n‚Ä¢ Liaise with your dedicated security provider to ascertain the feasibility